comments_2_select_up_to_five:
Large off leash dog areas, possibly fenced in.
Separate from this, real free play nature playgrounds for children and preteens, with rocks and logs to climb, creeks they are allowed into, and imaginative play. In Germany, for example, my small hometown has such a playground with metal sculptures the kids can fill with river rocks, a small creek with stepping stones they can build dams in with more rocks. There are goats in a pasture next to it. Both goats and children can climb up into a large wooden boat via bridges and ladders. Open ended imagination play.
_3_select_up_to_five_5_options: Nature trails for hiking and walking; Nature-based play elements i.e. balancing log, stump jump, climbing boulders, etc.); Native plant demonstration gardens; Off leash dog areas; Outdoor pools
comments_3_select_up_to_five: I donâ€™t agree. In Germany, we saw a nature playground that was much more involving: there was a creek kids could build dams in with rocks. There were pet goats behind a fence. A huge wooden boat the kids and goats could climb from two sides and meet at the top (separately). Various tree houses and shelters they could play house in, all made of natural materials. It kept them engaged for hours.

name: Jimmy Stanley
comments_2_select_up_to_five: I walk the beautiful Hike and Bike Trail every morning at 6:30AM. Thankfully, at that time, there is seldom a motorized scooter to buzz me. Later they come out. The city is irresponsible in not enforcing the law we have prohibiting motorized scooters on the trail. What good is a law if it is not enforced. Three days ago I saw two adults on scooters with a child on their scooter with them. If they had fallen forward, it would have crushed the face of the child. Irresponsible adults and irresponsible city officials for allowing that. The quality of my experience on the trail has gone down. A friend and I were talking this morning about why the law has not been enforced on the trail. We were wondering if the city officials were wined and dined and maybe received campaign contributions for not enforcing the law on the trail. There has to be some reason.
_3_select_up_to_five_5_options: Off leash dog areas; Disc golf; Nature trails for hiking and walking

comments_32_golf_courses: It costs $15 to play Hancock Golf Course, $21 to Play Morris Williams, Lions, Jimmy Clay or Kizer. The cost of a set of clubs is equivalent to the cost of a bicycle.;  Golf is the only enterprise fund within the city, meaning the courses generate revenue to cover their operating expenses. What that means is that  little to no tax money from the general fund is used for golf courses;  The city golf courses use effluent water from the city water treatment plants, so it assists in dispersing this reclaimed, non-potable water.  The cost of a round of golf is usually equivalent to the cost of a movie ticket and a bucket of popcorn.

comments_2_select_up_to_five: No extra junk. These are our open, natural spaces of repose, respite  and recovery. Austinites already give away several weeks per year to big commercial operations like ACL. Don't take away any more of our access.  You have enough trouble maintaining the trails, vegetation and erosion control as it is. Where would COA/PARD get the money for extra programs?  I certainly don't want to pay for them. Our parks are not a profit-or-loss operation.  We pay for our use.  The imposition of commercial, for- profit businesses on public space is also a non-starter. Keep  profit out of the parks.  The only physical addition to the parks that would be of value to a large number of park-goers would be to add foot-level lighting along the trails to enable  safe use after dark.

comments_3_select_up_to_five: Please keep our parks tranquil. Do not crowd them with unnecessary activities. The pools have been a vital part of our parks for generations. Let's keep those maintained and open to the public for no entrance fees.
comments_4_select_up_to_three: Keep our parks open and tranquil! Stop trying to fill the open spaces with money-making operations.
comments_5_select_up_to_three: Please keep the pools open for the neighborhood kids, maybe add hours for seniors during the days. But most important, keep our parks tranquil and open. Do not use the parks for commercial ventures. They are NOT entertainment venues, they are commons.
comments_6_select_up_to_three: If there are to be arts programs, they should pertain the the local neighborhood culture and not be brought in from outside. comments_8_what_would: Benches in our parks so we elders can sit and rest.

comments_11_as_austin_invests: The pools play an important role. We saw a brochure a couple of years ago extolling the virtues of water parks which some other cities have bought into. Kids in our area grew up with the pools and say they were an important part of childhood. Otherwise, we need to keep our parks tranquil and open.

Dolores Park in San Francisco is a good example of a park that provides structures for a large range of ages. The very very very large slide gives kids great exercise. There should be rolling treadmills. There should also be a variety of swings and ziplines like those at play for all Park in round Rock. It would be nice if parks had a combination of trails and play structures. Exercise equipment is great to.;  Play structures that were far more challenging and designed for older people. For example the play structures at Dolores Park in San Francisco are geared towards people of many abilities. The large concrete slides at Codornices Park in Berkeley and Koret Park in SF are wonderful.  The middle level of Glendale La Loma Park in Berkeley also has more challenging structures.

Our city is woefully under funding aquatics.

comments_2_select_up_to_five: Why no swimming pools listed? Swimming is an activity that seniors and people with joint problems can participate in when they can't do other exercising. With increased aging, our city needs to provide accessible to people of all ages, not just bike riding millennials. Also, with increased temperatures, pools provide a cool exercise opportunity in the face of climate change. COA needs to provide outdoor pools April through October instead of just in the three summer months. Our city is woefully underfunding aquatics.;  No swimming pools listed as part of parks? As our community ages, we need to fully fund and maintain pool facilities since swimming and water fitness classes are the best exercise for seniors or people who have limited mobility on land. Also with increased temperatures in Austin, having outdoor pools for residents to use from April to November is a basic necessity.

No.  Mowing  to the edge of creek banks reduces the important infiltration/sponge function of riparian vegetation.  If you mow to create a "lawn" you increase the chances of flooding. Austin Watershed Protection has evolved beyond the "mow to the edge of the creek" mentality  thanks to scientific evidence and so should you.;  Who exactly is going to enforce the speed limit???

comments_2_select_up_to_five: Specifically Emma Long Metro Park needs forest management. It's now a tinder box of dead trees and the park has started putting rocks and brush (including two dumps of chipped wood along the street to discourage road side parking. Very ugly and a fire hazard. Why put burnable barriers to stop cars from parking along the street when no parking signs would work just fine? What good are the hiking trails if one can't park to use them? What about cars that have to pull over in an emergency that will now have to stop on the pavement? All that is going to happen is the park goers are going to park on Pearce Rd. (a county street) in a neighborhood where that street is narrow and winding and thus very dangerous. Keep your parking problems in the park, not push it off into the bordering county roads.

name: Margaret & Heinz Aeschbach
comments_2_select_up_to_five: We like to birdwatch in the greenspace beside the south side of the pool and along the creek to Lou Neff Point.  Yesterday we saw 30 species in 2 hours!  One bird that we often see is "rare":  the Couch's kingbird.  He was spotted in the tall cottonwood trees between the railroad tracks and the Butler Park.  We are very happy that the city has allowed "our space" (a triangle between Barton Hills Dr. and the Butler trail) to "grow".  This year we are seeing many wintering finches and sparrows along with the usual cardinals, wrens, mocking birds, blue jays, and hawks.

name: Phil
comments_2_select_up_to_five: As an owner of a dog that's never coming off leash anywhere but her home and yard I am against expansion of off leash parks that aren't fenced.  I have run into trouble with off leash dogs, both stray and owner accompanied, that feel it absolutely necessary to approach my leashed dog and I.  Once I had to lift my 65 pound dog off another dog to save the other dogs lower jaw from being ripped off its face.  My dog is strong but is not aggressive at all towards other dogs we encounter on our runs through the streets and parks around NW Austin.  It's when they insist on running across a field of a ON LEASH ONLY park and attempt to jam their snout into my dogs rear after having been shooed away 3 times already that the stuff happens.  I have a right to take my dog running at an ON LEASH ONLY park and not have to deal with some fool's stupid off leash dog!

comments_2_select_up_to_five: I live near Davis and Brodie in the Maple Run area and there's no neighborhood park.  PARD should consider a partnership with Boone Elementary to help provide that park space.

Have two weekend days a month on the Hike and Bike trail with no scooters and no bikes. It is so stressful around Town Lake on the weekends that we almost never go there anymore.;  Cleaner - e.g., Waller Creek between 6th and 9th Streets - not sure whether that's a park, but it was ABSOLUTELY DISGUSTING when we walked through there on the way to the Waller lights.  Trash, mud, urine, .... I didn't realize that the lights were in a different spot from the last year that we had seen them, so we just walked north. Thank goodness we didn't have out-of-town guests. I'm used to going places I've never been before for a little adventure, but THAT was probably about as interesting as a dumpster dive might be.

This park is a true native gem. It fosters a great mix of hiking and walking down to the beautiful constant level Lake Austin.
The park is very simple and has a great open field at the "lake." (Colorado river's south bank) A permanent volleyball net is 
perfect and well used on weekends. The main thing needed is to fill in the potholes on the narrow asphalt road in the park. Parking is a problem. The drop off at the edges of the asphalt are difficult, especially for smaller vehicles. The small covered dock with picnic tables is perfect. It is a great, quiet space for amazing bird watching. 
People fish on the banks of an inlet fed by a creek. The new benches are good. Please continue the "Native Prairie" restoration in the open field where cattle used to graze. Wildlife needs this river corridor left as open as possible. There  is a nature preserve
on the opposite river bank. thanks

comments_10_what_is_the_most: Our former community (PLymouth, MN) released 2-4 catalogs a year detailing upcoming registration opportunities for the community. It also included community events (with complete event details). Registration occurred online but families used these catalogs heavily to see every thing going on in the community for the upcoming six months. The summer catalogs in particular were highly anticipated and many camps and classes filled the first day of Registration.
